AI Trader — Day 1 Summary
Project: ai-trader — autonomous paper trading bot (Alpaca + PicoClaw)
Platform: Python 3.10+, Raspberry Pi target (gamer@alarm)
Day 1 focus: Turn a working trading loop into an observable, operable agent with live visibility and memory

Starting Point (Before Day 1)
The core trading engine already existed and was running on the Pi:

Alpaca paper execution, risk manager, portfolio tracking
Multi-stage radar pipeline (~120 stocks + ~40 crypto universe → promote → deep scan)
Strategies: momentum, mean reversion, volatility
PicoClaw AI layer (JSON decisions per cycle)
Hybrid watchlist (pinned symbols + CoinGecko dynamic crypto)
Rich scroll-print dashboard — one static dump per ~5-minute cycle
Logging: logs/trades.json, logs/state.json, logs/events.jsonl
Gap: The bot was trading autonomously but was hard to see, steer, or learn from. No live UI, no operator commands, no AI memory across cycles.

Day 1 Goal: Three Major Priorities
User-defined roadmap for Day 1:

Interactive Dashboard (highest priority) — live visibility into system state, radar, AI, risk, and a SOC-style timeline
Agent Interaction Layer — operator commands and runtime control without mutating .env
AI Memory / Reflection — compressed cross-cycle context injected into prompts
All three were implemented in a single build pass.

Priority 1: Textual Live Dashboard (“NEURAL TRADER”)
Replaced the legacy Rich scroll dashboard with a Textual TUI as the default UI (python main.py), keeping --plain for legacy Rich mode over SSH debugging.

Dashboard panels
Header bar — mode (PAPER/LIVE), cycle count, strategy, market regime, pause state, countdown
Account — equity, buying power, day P&L
Positions — open holdings with unrealized P&L
Pending orders — queued/unfilled orders
RADAR — top radar hits (score, 1D%, vol, spike flag)
VOL RANK — deep-scan opportunity ranking
CRYPTO / STOCKS — split watchlist tables with position/pending tags
AI DECISION — symbol, action, confidence, reason + memory mood/bias/lesson
RISK — halt state, day P&L, cooldowns, max position
Timeline — SOC-style scrolling event feed
Command bar — natural-language operator input
